  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Brief Preface to the Illustrated Treatise on Acupuncture and Moxibustion of the Bronze Figure
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant respectfully reflects upon the *Classic of the Luminous Hall*—wherein the Yellow Emperor and Qi Bo once brought life to all under heaven. Those who subsequently crafted the Bronze Figure with its acupuncture points followed in their footsteps, preserving and transmitting their wisdom. Indeed, the people are the vital breath of the state; when the vital breath sickens, the body itself trembles toward ruin. The ancient sages taught through ritual propriety to nourish the heart and spirit, provided sustenance to nourish the flesh, and administered medicine to harmonize the blood and qi—thus protecting the vital breath and granting longevity to the nation's lifeblood. Therefore, the arts of acupuncture and moxibustion are themselves an aspect of benevolent governance.

    Your servant humbly observes that the Sovereign's virtue of cherishing life mirrors that of the ancients. The teachings for cultivating the people have reached their perfection, yet His Highness, as though viewing the people's afflictions as his own body's pain, remains ever watchful, day and night. Our Eastern realm, isolated upon the margins of the sea, finds master physicians scarce, the illustrated texts often corrupted, and complete methods of needlework rarely beheld. Thus in the summer of the fifteenth year of Yongle, petition was made to request the Bronze Figure of Acupuncture and Moxibustion. The Son of Heaven approved, and the Imperial Physician's Court was commanded to render two scrolls—one of the front view and one of the back. The precision of these illustrations is flawless to the finest hair—as if one stood before the legendary healers Hua Tuo and Bian Que themselves, receiving instruction directly. Truly, they are a compass for saving lives. The Sovereign forthwith ordered these images carved into wooden blocks and distributed throughout the realm, that all generations might receive their benefit. Such virtue of cherishing the people and such care in preserving the nation's lifeblood—all is complete. And so this realm shall be elevated into an age of peace and longevity. Alas, how sublime this is!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The *Classic of the Luminous Hall* (明堂正經): An ancient medical text attributed to the legendary Yellow Emperor and the sage physician Qi Bo.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hua Tuo and Bian Que: Legendary physicians of ancient China, invoked here as exemplars of medical excellence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yongle fifteenth year (永樂乙未): Corresponding to 1425 CE, when the Korean court received the Bronze Figure illustrations from Ming China.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Bronze Figure (銅人): A famous Ming Dynasty anatomical model showing acupuncture points, used for both medical instruction and training.'
